<h2 id="CalcViewActi">1. The Calculative View of Action</h2>

<p>
The most prominent advocates of the calculative view of action are
Candace Vogler and Michael Thompson. We will start with Vogler&rsquo;s
version of the view, then proceed to Thompson&rsquo;s.</p>

<p>
Call <em>psychologism</em> the claim that the right way to do logic
and the theory of rationality more generally is first to figure out
how the mind works. Since the early seventies, almost all mainstream
work on practical reasoning has been psychologistic in this sense; a
representative example is Michael Smith&rsquo;s argument for the
&lsquo;Humean theory of motivation&rsquo;, which turns on what desires
are, and how they work (Smith 1987). Vogler&rsquo;s treatment of
practical rationality (Vogler 2002) is a sharp departure from the
common approach, an attempt to replicate the anti-psychologistic turn
which Frege and Husserl imparted to work on theoretical rationality
in, respectively, the analytic and Continental traditions. She takes
herself to be following G. E. M. Anscombe (Vogler 2001), who was in
turn following Aquinas. (We will fill in some of the Anscombean
backstory below, but otherwise will not take up the historical
background to the work under discussion; however, see the entry on
 <a href="../practical-reason-med/">medieval theories of practical reason</a>.)</p>
 
<p>
Vogler notices that instrumentalism &ndash; the view that all reasons
for action are means-end reasons &ndash; is the default view in
contemporary philosophy. There must, she infers, be a compelling
insight at the bottom of it; but instrumentalism has been much-refuted
over the past few decades. What these refutations of instrumentalism
show, Vogler believes, is that formulating the underlying insight
psychologistically (as a thesis about mental operations and the mental
states involved in them) results in weak and unsustainable renditions
of it. She concludes that to articulate what instrumentalism is
getting right, you have to strip away the psychologism.</p>

<p>
On one reading of Frege, the proper way to do logic is not to look
inward, as it were to the gears of the mind, but outward, to the
logical relations that hold between suitably abstract objects, and to
read the correct inference patterns off of these Frege, 1984). In the
practical analog of this move, when you look outward, what you find
are actions, the external products of any successful deployment of
practical reasons. So the logic of practical reasons is to be read off
the structure of actions in something like the way that, say,
truth-functional logic is to be read off the truth-functional
relations between propositions. This form of anti-psychologism
preempts a worry one might have had about what was described at the
outset as the organizing argument of the action-oriented approach. The
proposal, recall, was to read the inference patterns off the structure
of actions; if one were to construe this as reconstructing the process
of practical reasoning from its product, how far would the
reconstruction be likely to get? But Vogler&rsquo;s anti-psychologism
insists that questions about rationality are not questions about what
<em>processes</em> of thought lead up to a decision.</p>

<p>
For Vogler, intentional actions are picked out and segmented into
their parts by applications of Anscombe&rsquo;s
&lsquo;Why?&rsquo;-questions. (&lsquo;Why are you chopping the
nuts?&rsquo; &lsquo;I&rsquo;m making a salad.&rsquo;) The internal
structure of actions is consequently a series of steps towards a
termination point (or &lsquo;end&rsquo;), a place where the action
<em>stops</em>. When you make Deborah Madison&rsquo;s persimmon and
hazelnut salad, you first coarsely chop the nuts; then you thinly
slice three Fuyu persimmons crosswise and put them in a bowl with the
nuts; then you add three handfuls of trimmed watercress; then you toss
with the dressing &ndash; and you&rsquo;re done. A step can be shown
to be rational by showing it to be a step on the way to the
termination point of the action that you are performing. A step can be
shown to be <em>ir</em>rational by showing that it&rsquo;s not: for
instance, if you&rsquo;ve finished making the salad, but you
obsessively keep chopping nuts. (Vogler allows that there may be
&ldquo;atomic actions&rdquo;, actions that do not have further actions
as their parts; perhaps blinking is an example. But just about any
action we care about will be a complex action.)</p>

<p>
Vogler&rsquo;s &lsquo;calculative view&rsquo; is accordingly that
whenever (or perhaps, <em>almost</em> whenever) you have a reason to
do something, you have a calculative reason, that is, a reason whose
force is: this is a step toward the termination point of my action or
a part of its larger whole. She does not insist that there are no
other sorts of practical consideration. In fact, she provides what she
takes to be an exhaustive list of the logical forms that the remaining
considerations can have. (See Millgram 2006 for a brief overview.)
Vogler&rsquo;s claim is that when you have a reason of one of these
further sorts, you must <em>also</em> have a calculative reason.</p>

<p>
This connection only runs one way. Since other sorts of practical
considerations organize, modulate and generally control actions, they
presuppose calculative reasons. Calculative structures (and the
reasons they give you) do not presuppose these other sorts of
consideration. Vogler regards theories in which actions must be
informed by, (say,) a large-scale conception of the good as modeling
practical rationality on a psychopathology akin to paranoia. This
asymmetry is what Vogler takes to be the deep insight underlying
instrumentalism: actions other than the atomic ones must have a
means-end (or part-whole) structure. Consequently, calculative (or
part-whole) reasons are fundamental; they are nonoptional, or
binding.</p>

<p>
This appeal to the structure of action as the foundation for practical
rationality has dramatic consequences for substantive moral theory.
Vogler casts her view as internalist in the sense that reasons for
action do not have to be the same for everybody. Since reasons other
than the calculative ones are optional for her, they vary from person
to person as well. But if that is correct, then you can be, as the
title of Vogler&rsquo;s book has it, reasonably vicious; immorality of
even the most extreme kind need not entail irrationality.</p>

<p>
Like Vogler&rsquo;s calculative view, Michael Thompson&rsquo;s account
of practical reasons is motivated by anti-psychologism. His account
reverses the direction of argument we observed in Vogler. In the, what
comes first is our grasp of inference (Thompson 2008, Part II). It is
an account of action that is being read off the inference patterns
(rather than the other way around), in something like the way Fregeans
of this stripe take us to read the logical form of propositions off
our command of truth-functional and quantificational inference. The
objective of the argument is to exploit an account of action in order
to establish a thesis about calculative practical reasons, namely,
that those reasons are not psychological states such as desires or
intentions.</p>

<p>
The argumentative strategy is adapted from Sellars (1997,
37&ndash;41); it bears comparison to related arguments in Nagel (1970,
29&ndash;31, and Brandom, 2001). A core practice of reason-giving is
identified, one that adduces only actions (and not psychological
states); Thompson then exhibits the point of introducing apparently
psychological locutions (such as &ldquo;because I want
to&hellip;&rdquo;) into such a practice. The explanation is supposed
to demonstrate that these locutions do not really name anything like
desires or intentions but are rather a roundabout way of conveying
information about the progress of an ongoing course of action. We will
first describe the way Thompson sets up the core practice, and then
briefly reconstruct his argument for non-psychologistic renderings of
apparently psychologically oriented reason locutions.</p>

<p>
Like Vogler, Thompson uses Anscombean &lsquo;Why?&rsquo;-questions to
pick out intentional actions. He then draws our attention to the way
grammatical aspect figures into their answers. Action descriptions can
be either perfective (&ldquo;I made the salad&rdquo;) or progressive
(&ldquo;I&rsquo;m making the salad,&rdquo; &ldquo;I was making the
salad&rdquo;). These grammatical forms are not merely ornamental; they
carry different implications. From the perfective &ldquo;I made a
salad,&rdquo; it follows that at some point there <em>was</em> a
salad. From the progressive &ldquo;I was making a salad,&rdquo; it
doesn&rsquo;t follow: perhaps I was interrupted by a phone call.
Thompson demarcates &lsquo;naive rationalizations&rsquo; as those
which deploy the progressive in placing one action as part of another.
(&ldquo;Why are you chopping the nuts?&rdquo; &ldquo;I&rsquo;m making
a salad.&rdquo;) The contrast is with &lsquo;sophisticated
rationalizations&rsquo;, which seem to invoke psychological states
like desires (&ldquo;I <em>want</em> to make a salad&rdquo;).</p>

<p>
We can imagine a society (call it the <em>action-theoretic state of
nature</em>) getting by with only naive rationalization. But there is
room for improvement in their practice of calculative reason-giving,
and here&rsquo;s a short way to see how. Agents restricted to naive
rationalizations will say &ldquo;I&rsquo;m <em>B</em>ing because
I&rsquo;m <em>A</em>ing,&rdquo; when <em>B</em>ing is an action that
is a part of <em>A</em>ing, and they are <em>A</em>ing. But such parts
of actions often come in sequence, one after another. So such an agent
can, at a particular time, be executing a containing action, i.e.,
<em>A</em>ing, but not executing a subsidiary action, <em>B</em>ing.
Now, if, at a particular time, an agent is not executing the
subsidiary action (<em>B</em>ing), then when someone asks if
he&rsquo;s <em>B</em>ing, he&rsquo;ll say he&rsquo;s not. This puts
agents restricted to naive rationalizations in the position of saying
both that they&rsquo;re <em>B</em>ing, and that they&rsquo;re not
<em>B</em>ing. (E.g., &ldquo;I&rsquo;m <em>B</em>ing because I&rsquo;m
<em>A</em>ing, but I&rsquo;m not <em>B</em>ing.&rdquo;) That&rsquo;s
potentially confusing.</p>

<p>
We can suppose that such agents will adopt devices to obviate the
confusion. For instance, they&rsquo;ll learn to say (as we do),
&ldquo;I&rsquo;m <em>B</em>ing tomorrow&rdquo; &ldquo;I&rsquo;m going
to <em>B</em>,&rdquo; &ldquo;I want to <em>A</em>,&rdquo; Each such
locution carries a different sort of additional information. For
instance, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m going to <em>B</em>&rdquo; positions one as
being in the very preliminary run-up phases of an action; when one
says, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m going to <em>B</em> because I&rsquo;m
<em>A</em>ing,&rdquo; one is giving a naive rationalization, but one
which registers that the <em>B</em>ing phase of <em>A</em>ing has not
yet arrived, even though the reason for the former is that it is part
of the latter. Likewise, &ldquo;I intend to <em>A</em>&rdquo; places
one merely at the planning phase of <em>A</em>ing; &ldquo;I want to
<em>A</em>,&rdquo; allows that one may be at a pre-planning phase. The
function of these locutions is to preempt confusion by placing the
actions that make up a naive rationalization in their temporal
sequence. But once we see that that <em>is</em> their function, the
temptation to construe them as invoking psychological states
(intentions, desires and so on) is misguided. The belief-desire
theorist of practical rationality is treating a linguistic device for
sorting out the order of subsidiary actions (&ldquo;&hellip;because I
want to&hellip;&rdquo;) as naming a motivating psychological state (a
desire).</p>

<p>
Both Vogler&rsquo;s and Thompson&rsquo;s views position themselves as
descendants of Elizabeth Anscombe&rsquo;s short classic monograph
<em>Intention</em> (1985), so it will be helpful to contrast her model
of action briefly with the later appropriations we have just surveyed.
The centerpiece of that work is a famous description of a particular
structure of nested actions: a man is moving his arm up and down;
doing so is operating a pump; that in turn is conveying water up to a
house; doing <em>that</em> is poisoning the occupants of the house;
that, finally, is effecting what goes by the label &lsquo;regime
change&rsquo;. A single core action, the ongoing movement of that arm,
is repeatedly recharacterized, by invoking progressively broader
contexts. Those in-order-to connections can be elicited from the agent
through a series of the &lsquo;Why?&rsquo;-questions mentioned above:
&ldquo;Why are you pumping?&rdquo; &ldquo;To get the water up to the
building.&rdquo; &ldquo;Why are you doing that?&rdquo; &ldquo;To kill
every last one of them.&rdquo; (In this work especially, Anscombe made
a point of nonmoralistic illustrations.)</p>

<p>
We can flag some of the ways in which her treatment and those of her
successors diverge. Where Anscombe attended primarily to single core
activities placed in broader contexts, Vogler focuses on sequences of
distinct activities. Where Thompson&rsquo;s actions are always
composed of yet-smaller actions, Anscombe allows that below that core
action of arm movement, the activity in question is, as she puts it,
preintentional: normally, when someone pumping water flexes the
muscles in his arm, it is not an additional nested intentional action.
This fact is marked by his inability to say how he&rsquo;s doing it,
which is a denial of the central condition for an action&rsquo;s being
intentional, namely, that when you do it, you know what you&rsquo;re
doing.</p>

<p>
Anscombe argues that an action as a whole, that is, under the
outermost characterization in the matryoshka-doll structure, needs to
have a <em>point</em> &ndash; to come with a &lsquo;desirability
characterization&rsquo; &ndash; if it is to be intelligible as an
action at all. For instance, it might be for the sake of pleasure, or
health, or, in the pumping illustration, regime change might be cast
as matter of aspiring to a better future, where these are not
understood as further layers of the onion-like construction (in that
latter case, because the agent doesn&rsquo;t have enough of a sense of
<em>how</em> regime change is supposed to bring about that better
future). But the investigation of desirability characterizations
&ndash; and of whether there&rsquo;s a difference between a
<em>point</em> and a <em>reason</em> &ndash; is left incomplete.
(Amusingly, she says at one point where the question might have gotten
attention: &ldquo;I say &lsquo;Consider this&rsquo; really with a view
to saying &lsquo;let us not consider it here&rsquo;&rdquo; [sec.
13]).</p>

<h2 id="AuthViewActi">2. The Authorship View of Action</h2>

<p>
A second approach takes the essential feature of action to be that it
is <em>authored</em>; there is no such thing as an action without an
owner. The two most developed positions of this kind are due to
Christine M. Korsgaard and J. David Velleman.</p>

<p>
On Korsgaard&rsquo;s view, what gives an action an owner is that it is
attributable to the person <em>as a whole.</em> Whole-person
attributions require a <em>constitution</em>, a form of psychic
organization and regulation of a person that is a smaller-scale analog
of the political constitution of a state. A person&rsquo;s
constitutions contains the procedures by which actions are to be
produced; one&rsquo;s behaviors count as full-fledged actions, only
when they are produced in that way (Korsgaard 2008, ch. 3, Korsgaard
2009). In contrast to the views we have so far surveyed,
Korsgaard&rsquo;s theory of practical rationality is psychologistic.
The nature of action is the starting point of an argument used to
determine the proper structure of an agent&rsquo;s psychology: we ask
what psychological structure an agent must have in place for him to be
able to author actions. And that psychology in turn determines what
the correct forms of practical inference must be.</p>

<p>
The philosophical motivations of Korsgaard&rsquo;s position are in
part forensic: the connection between actions and agents must be such
that we can hold agents responsible for what they do. More
importantly, the account is meant to explain why your practical
reasons are binding: what their &lsquo;normative force&rsquo; is. Her
idea is that, failing to meet the constitutive standards for actions
produces a defective action; an action that an agent denies as her own
would be defective. Now, we <em>have</em> to act, because anything we
do will be an action. So, the question of why an item should conform
to the the constitutive standards for its type &rsquo;answers
itself&rsquo; (Korsgaard 2008, 61). If she can show that deploying
reasons satisfying certain requirements is a constitutive standard for
action &ndash; and the requirements she is gong to argue for are
Kantian &ndash; that will amount to showing why you should act on
reasons that satisfy those Kantian requirements.</p>

<p>
We noted that action is properly authored by an agent only when it is
produced by the agent as a whole. In order for the attribution of an
action to a person to be meaningful, there must be a real distinction
between <em>your</em> actions, on the one hand, and events that
resemble actions but are produced by your psychic parts, on the other.
We can make out such a distinction only if you identify with a
principle of choice that determines the action, where that principle
is universal in form. (We won&rsquo;t reconstruct her arguments for
that last claim here; Millgram 2011 gives a summary.) Having a
principle of choice contrasts mere <em>acts</em> (setting the table)
with <em>actions</em> (setting the table to be ready before the guests
arrive), where the principle binds the act to the end for which they
are performed. The principles of practical rationality are the
procedures in a satisfactory individual constitution legislating over
principles of choice. Reasons for action must be universal in form,
and Korsgaard argues that this entails the substantive correctness of
Kantian moral theory, at any rate that part of it which imposes a
universalizability requirement on practical reasons: very roughly, it
must be possible for you and everyone else jointly to act on the basis
of that universal-in-form principle, without assuring the frustration
of the end it mentions. (For further description of Kant&rsquo;s
account, see the section on the universal law of nature formula in the
entry on
 <a href="../kant-moral/">Kant&rsquo;s moral philosophy</a>.)</p>
 
<p>
Let&rsquo;s pause to mark some of the contrasts between two of the
theories of practical inference we have on the table. First of all,
Kantian maxims &ndash; the structured statements of intention on which
the universalizability requirement is imposed &ndash; have means-end
or calculative structure. So Vogler&rsquo;s requirement that actions
be calculatively well-formed, is compatible with Korsgaard&rsquo;s
view. But Korsgaard and Vogler differ over whether the
universalizability of maxims is mandatory. Now because the
universalizability test (the so-called CI-procedure) is applied to
one&rsquo;s maxims as they arise, and because they might be novel
ones, it remains an open question what the moral theory generated by
this theory of practical reasoning is. A handful of canonical dicta
are usually thought of as constituting its core: not to lie; to help
others; to develop one&rsquo;s talents. So, secondly, differing
conceptions of action give rise to starkly differing views of the
moral demands of rationality; on Vogler&rsquo;s view, the solely
calculative conception of action allows for rational agents who lie,
exploit others, and don&rsquo;t bother to improve themselves.
Korsgaard&rsquo;s account is morally more demanding because it is more
demanding about what it takes to be an action.</p>

<p>
An important contrast between these views has to do with how the
attributability of action is understood. Anscombean accounts construe
that attribution of action as having to do with the special way in
which you know what you&rsquo;re doing. Since you just <em>know</em>
what you&rsquo;re doing, its being <em>your</em> action takes care of
itself. In Korsgaard&rsquo;s picture, however, action attribution is a
task each agent has to manage by composing oneself to meet the
exigencies of agency. If Kantian moral theory is to be nonoptional,
the noncalculative Kantian reasons must be also. If the noncalculative
reasons are the source of authorship, then that must also be
demonstrably nonoptional. That necessity is practical. But if that is
the right way to reconstruct Korsgaard&rsquo;s position, there is a
worry to register, one that we are not yet able to meet, but to which
we will return briefly when the time comes to assess the state of play
of the field we are surveying. (For some of the back and forth, see
Enoch 2006, Ferrero 2009, Tubert 2010, Katsafanas 2013, ch. 2, Lavin
2017.)</p>

<p>
We generally take arguments built around practical necessity to be
responsible to and modulated by the urgency and force of the
necessity. The point is easier to see when we consider collective
agents, so let us take up Korsgaard&rsquo;s political analogy once
more. A state that aspires to having all activity within its
jurisdiction be its own actions is totalitarian. Democratic states
sometimes mobilize themselves in a way that approximates this extreme:
usually, in times of all-out war. For instance, during WWII, the
American government imposed rationing, managed a great deal of
industrial production directly, and so on. But when there is no such
need, liberals regard totalitarianism as an unreasonable and immoral
mode of political organization, preferring a state in which most
activity within is not attributable to it. Markets are an alternative
form of coordination: market outcomes are not directly attributable to
the state. In a market economy, competitors act independently and
against each other: coordination does not consist in forestalling
competition, but in creating a regulatory framework for it. If the
analogy goes through, action in Korsgaard&rsquo;s sense is inevitable
only insofar as practical demands on agency require totalitarian
rather than, say, market-like approaches to the organization of
individual activity. The worry is that we do not yet understand the
practical demands that <em>always</em> warrant forms of coordination
that underwrite the full attributability of action.</p>

<p>
Korsgaard&rsquo;s response is an argument that you cannot choose to
have a character with fault lines in it, one whose unity is
&lsquo;contingent and unstable&rsquo; (2009, 8.5.2). That argument is
too opaque to permit an uncontroversial reconstruction; instead I will
conclude the exposition of her position by describing the challenge
the argument is meant to meet. On Korsgaard&rsquo;s view, the
practical necessity of reconstituting one&rsquo;s agency from moment
to moment must be a formal feature of any human personality. However,
in our ordinary ways of thinking, practical necessities are
substantive and contingent pressures. The formal feature of agency
that replaces those substantive pressures is the commitment to sustain
one&rsquo;s agency in any circumstances whatsoever: &lsquo;our
principles, moral principles, are supposed to hold us together in any
environment, any circumstance, come what may&rsquo; (Korsgaard 2009,
sec. 5.5.3). That commitment is supposed to be what makes action,
rather than a more loosely organized alternative to it, always our
plight.</p>

<p>
We turn now to the second of the positions that takes authorship to be
the essential feature of action. Like Korsgaard, Velleman takes
action, as contrasted with mere activity, to be owned (Velleman 2015,
101 and ch. 5, <em>passim</em>). Like Korsgaard, he takes ownership to
require a definite structure in an agent, and again like her, he takes
the forms of practical reasoning and substantive practical reasons to
be determined by the agent&rsquo;s structure. However, he disagrees
with Korsgaard about what the structure of an agent is, what its
practical reasons are, and incidentally, with Korsgaard&rsquo;s
insistence that being authored by the agent as a whole means not being
authored by a proper part of the agent. Velleman&rsquo;s position
makes more sense bearing in mind that it has more than one agenda;
accordingly we will juxtapose two complementary entry points, and
subsequently suggest that what looks like a third and independent
motivation for the view is reachable from those.</p>

<p>
The sense of ownership at work in Velleman&rsquo;s view is inherited
from an older debate about freedom of the will and autonomy, and it
has to do with whether the agent can honestly dissociate himself from
his action or motivation (e.g., &ldquo;It wasn&rsquo;t really me
speaking; it was just the alcohol&rdquo;). One might think that this
sort of dissociation could be overcome by a further endorsement
(&ldquo;It really <em>was</em> me speaking&rdquo;), but a familiar
difficulty is that many forms of endorsement merely raise the problem
anew: ownership cannot be identified with an endorsement when the
agent can dissociate himself from that endorsement as well (Velleman
2015, 295&ndash;296). There is an extensive literature on agency built
up of rounds of this back-and-forth, and here is a very quick taste of
it. Harry Frankfurt had suggested that a desire is full-fledgedly
yours when you have a suitable second-order desire (a desire that the
initial desire motivate you to act; Frankfurt 1971); Gary Watson
pointed out that Frankfurt&rsquo;s proposal merely pushed the question
back to whether that second-order desire was full-fledgedly yours, and
he proposed fit with your values as an alternative account (Watson
1975). But the rejoinder was of course to ask what makes a set of
values full-fledgedly your own (Benson 1987), and the problem seemed
to take on the shape of a hard-to-halt regress. (For more on this
debate, see Section 2.4 of the entry on
 <a href="../freewill/">free will</a>.)</p>
 
<p>
Velleman&rsquo;s way of terminating the regress is to locate a
psychological element from which an agent cannot dissociate himself
(2015, chs. 5, 7). Because to act is to act for reasons, an agent
cannot dissociate himself from a desire to act for reasons &ndash;
not, that is, without ceasing to be an agent. (Treat the content of
that desire as a temporary placeholder; we&rsquo;ll return to it
shortly. In addition, Watson 2004, esp. at 28, 166f, 168 n. 7,
registers dissent: to terminate a regress, what&rsquo;s needed is not
a mental state you can&rsquo;t disown.) When such a desire contributes
in the canonical manner to producing an action (say, by weighing in on
the side of other desires that it endorses, and so tipping the
decision toward that action), we say that the agent produces the
action. So, to recapitulate, actions are in the first place
<em>owned.</em> An action is owned, in the relevant sense, when it
cannot be disowned; the only anchor for an action that an agent cannot
disown without ceasing to be an agent is (roughly) the desire to act
for reasons. So what it takes to be an action is to be (appropriately)
produced by such a desire.</p>

<p>
An action is what is produced by the operation of this desire, and so
this desire amounts to the constitutive aim of action (in something
like the way, Velleman thinks, that truth is the constitutive aim of
belief [2015, ch. 10]). It thus serves to determine what putative
reasons for action <em>are</em> (good) practical reasons (in something
like the way that truth determines what reasons for belief are good
reasons). But then its content cannot quite be: to act for reasons.
For that would amount to a viciously circular and vacuous
specification of the constitutive aim of action. Velleman&rsquo;s
alternative specification of the content is (roughly again, because
there is some room for variation) to know what one is doing when one
acts, or to make sense to oneself when one acts (Velleman 1989). So
what counts as a (good) practical reason is that which makes
one&rsquo;s actions intelligible to oneself. Velleman seems originally
to have had something like the following schema in mind: desires
motivate, and so explain actions; when you act on the basis of a
desire, your action makes sense to you; when your desire to make sense
to yourself, together with more occasion-specific desires, produces an
action serving the occasion-specific desires, that is a full-fledged
action on your own part, and not mere activity.</p>

<p>
That default schema looks to be a version of the authorship view of
action supporting an instrumentalist or means-end (rather than, as in
Korsgaard&rsquo;s development of it, a Kantian) account of practical
reasons. However, as Velleman&rsquo;s position has evolved, he has
suggested further patterns. Often one emotion naturally gives rise to
another, as when (in one familiar pop-psychology meme), denial of a
loss is supposed to be followed by anger, which is in turn succeeded
by bargaining, followed ultimately by acceptance. Such cascades of
emotion are the spines of narratives, and an action is rendered
narratively intelligible in following such a cascade (Velleman 2009,
191, 194&ndash;197). Thus, when supported by a desire to be
intelligible to oneself, narratives give rise to actions. Instrumental
reasons have now been supplemented by what Velleman construes as
narrative reasons. In later work, Velleman has further proposed
character for the explanatory role (2009, ch. 1): if you stay in
character (in the way that actors on stage aim at), what you do will
make sense to you, and being motivated by the desire to make sense to
yourself, what you do will count as an action. (A bit of nuance: in
his earlier work, Velleman took the relevant desire to be a
substantive motivation, on a par with other desires in the cognitive
mix, but he has since relaxed the characterization; we can perhaps
more properly think of it as a drive, implemented as a structural
feature of a cognitive system, rather than one of the items moved
around inside that system. (Compare Velleman 2015, 169, 246.)</p>

<p>
Now, notice what one&rsquo;s reasons for action will turn out to be,
formally. Once again, because reasons for action are picked out as
what would explain one&rsquo;s actions, we cannot, on pain of
circularity, gloss what it is to be a satisfactory explanation of an
action as being a practical reason (cf. Velleman 2009, 40). So we will
instead rely on an already available notion of explanation and,
Velleman concludes, it must be <em>theoretical</em>, i.e., logically
the same sort of explanation that would account for any matter of
fact. Returning to the default schema for an illustration, desires are
reasons because they (potentially) explain action, and they explain
action in the first place because they <em>causally</em> explain it.
Here is the a second and equally important motivation for the
position.</p>

<p>
It is typically common ground in this field that there are two deeply
different but parallel modes of rationality: theoretical and
practical. Philosophers tend to see inference about matters of fact as
relatively unproblematic; to a first approximation, it is when you
reliably derive truths from truths. Practical reasoning is seen as an
analogous enterprise, one which is, however, much more opaque: in
determining what to do, as opposed to what to believe, it is much less
clear when it is being executed correctly. Velleman eliminates the
commonly accepted distinction by reducing practical to theoretical
rationality, reducing problems about the correctness of practical
inference to problems in the philosophy of explanation. Facts explain
facts; so the move requires construing decisions as factual
conclusions. The live candidate is that they are predictions of
one&rsquo;s actions (Velleman 2015, ch. 3). They differ from other
predictions in being self-fulfilling. (It&rsquo;s noteworthy that
Velleman has worked his way around to adopting and defending a view
which Anscombe 1985, sec. 2, entertains and rejects.) Thus, an action
proper will be such a prediction fulfilling itself; practical
reasoning will be the explanation of future behavior that underwrites
the self-fulfilling prediction of that behavior.</p>

<p>
A third motivation, which is at first glance independent, is to
account for a thesis that has received a great deal of attention
recently; namely, that when you act, you know what you&rsquo;re doing.
When you do things in order to make sense to yourself, you end up by
and large knowing what you&rsquo;re doing. Thus, the pervasiveness of
practical self-knowledge is explained by invoking a desire for it. The
desire is claimed both to be constitutive of agency and announced to
be empirically present in a normal human psychology. Now, a common
response to Velleman&rsquo;s insistence (2009, 136&ndash;138, 2015,
325) that people want to understand what they&rsquo;re doing &ndash;
and that this is part and parcel of their desire to understand the
universe &ndash; is incredulity. Remember where those responses are
coming from: academics teaching large introductory courses look out on
seas of apathetic faces that don&rsquo;t seem to care about
understanding much at all. Those same academics are committed to
research &ndash; which, as the saying has it, is what you&rsquo;re
doing when you don&rsquo;t know what you&rsquo;re doing.</p>

<p>
Velleman adduces the cognitive dissonance and attribution literatures
as further confirming evidence (Velleman 2009, 37f; Cooper 2007 is an
overview of the former), but his readers balk here also: the striking
feature of cognitive dissonance reduction is that subjects are unaware
that they exhibit it and are perturbed when it is pointed out to them.
Velleman himself notices that what he &lsquo;regard[s] as the height
of rationality&rsquo; others &lsquo;tend to regard... as
irrational&rsquo; (2009, 92 n. 4). What Velleman takes as practical
rationality in operation seems irrational to the agents themselves; it
requires, precisely, not understanding what one is doing. However, the
thesis that one desires practical self-knowledge was reached from the
entry points already introduced, and if our reading of the pressures
on the view is correct, the inalienable drive toward self-knowledge is
best construed as a cognitive <em>requirement</em>, one derived from
the need to anchor action attribution and the demand that practical
rationality be reduced to theoretical rationality.</p>

<p>
There might look to be a pair of related circularities hidden in
Velleman&rsquo;s account. The presumption that desires or more
generally motivations explain action is plausibly a legacy of a theory
of practical rationality on which desires are <em>reasons</em> for
action &ndash; and therefore, it is concluded, their causes. (As Quinn
1994, 236&ndash;239, points out, if desires are thought of as brute
causes, desire-driven behavior looks like Obsessive-Compulsive
Disorder, rather than rational action.) Similarly, the idea that a
given emotion naturally generates a particular successor emotion has
often been taken to be the result of training in narrative forms,
patterns that must be <em>already</em> culturally available. (For
something like this latter view, see Nussbaum 1992, ch. 12; Velleman
responds at 2009, 199 n. 15.) So theories of practical or narrative
rationality would come first, because they are presupposed by causal
explanations appealing to desires or narratives (2009, 26f). Such
theories would render the account viciously circular, and (the
objection concludes) are off-limits to Velleman&rsquo;s project.</p>

<p>
Velleman has an answer waiting in the wings, however. He, like other
theorists we have surveyed, has a finish line in moral theory, a
position he calls &lsquo;kinda Kantian&rsquo; (2009, 149): because our
lives are pervaded by the motivation to understand ourselves, over
time that motivation is likely to have deep effects. Specifically, we
will simplify our typology of persons and gradually <em>come to
be</em> agents for whom Kantian moral theory is a pretty decent fit,
thereby making ourselves easier to understand. That treatment can
serve as a model for understanding the psychological processes to
which Velleman appeals, and which renders the circularities we were
floating no longer vicious: perhaps we have gradually come to be
agents of whom belief-desire psychology is true, and in whom one
particular emotion naturally follows on another, because conforming to
these simple-minded theories simplified our personal and social lives,
making it easier for us to understand ourselves. In that case, the
causal factors these views invoke are now elements of
straightforwardly causal explanations, and it no longer matters how
they got that way.</p>

<p>
Recapping, on one authorship view, an action is a prediction being
enacted in part on the basis of a designated motivation, and practical
reasons are the explanatory support for such predictions. A second
such view supports a theory on which only universalizable maxims count
as practical reasons. (For a general criticism that both
self-knowledge and agential unity are matters of degree, and that
neither Velleman nor Korsgaard have the resources to construct the
comparative notion we need, see Katsafanas 2013, chs. 3 and 4.) We are
also seeing that authorship views of action may have strikingly
different philosophical motivations: in one case, to account for the
bindingness or normativity of reasons; in the other case, to
assimilate practical to theoretical reasoning, as well as a need to
make room for a certain sort of first-person authority about
one&rsquo;s will.</p>

<p>
We now turn to Paul Katsafanas&rsquo;s positive view.</p>

<h2 id="ChalSeekViewActi">3. The Challenge-Seeking View of Action</h2>

<p>
Actions, Katsafanas holds, are generated by drives. (Katsafanas 2013,
ch. 6; he attributes most of the elements of his view to Nietzsche,
this among them, but we won&rsquo;t be concerned with whether the
historical claim is correct.) So if there is a characteristic that
actions must have insofar as they are generated by drives, then all
actions have it. Drives are characterized by their aims and they
generate objects, typically, objects of desire. For instance, the aim
of the shopping drive is having lots of stuff. When an object is
attained (when you bring home that gewgaw from the craft store), the
desire for it evaporates, and you are satiated; but after a while, the
drive generates a new object (a new trendy shirt.) That drives
generate one object of desire after another can be characterized more
deeply as directed toward encountering and overcoming resistance.</p>

<p>
Now actions are the products of choice, and often enough result from
deliberation; when you deliberate, you take the outcome of
deliberation to settle what you are going to do. Even when
deliberation is absent, choice involves assessment, and that
determines you to act only if you approve the action; therefore,
actions aspire to be <em>active</em>, meaning you approve of what you
do. Further, if you understood what the motivational inputs to the
deliberative runup to the action really were, you would continue to
approve (Katsafanas 2013, ch. 5). That last demand covers all inputs,
not just the official ones, as when you claim to be weighing the pros
and cons of a request, but are also responsive to the attractiveness,
social class, or gender of the one making it. Because actions are
produced by drives, you can only be fully active if you approve of
your drives&rsquo; role; that in turn requires approving of the
drives&rsquo; primary structural feature, namely their ongoing
production of challenging goals. It follows that whenever we do
something, we have or aspire to have, if we are less than fully
active, a further aim. Borrowing Nietzsche&rsquo;s vocabulary,
Katsafanas dubs it &lsquo;will to power&rsquo;: selecting and
structuring our activities so they involve challenges we exert
ourselves in meeting.</p>

<p>
As in Velleman&rsquo;s view, the upshot is that your various reasons
are invariably accompanied by a further reason: choosing more rather
than less challenging &ndash; but nonetheless attainable &ndash;
objectives. Katsafanas takes this interest to answer the complaint he
directed at authorship views of action. If you approve of an aim, you
want to achieve it to the greatest extent possible; therefore, if you
are active, you are committed to more rather than to less challenging
activities. (However, as Anderson 2013, sec. 2.C points out:
Schopenhauer did not take the fact that one is motivated by
one&rsquo;s drives to entail this interest or a positive assessment of
either one&rsquo;s striving or one&rsquo;s actions. A life of endless
unsatisfied striving is, he thought, a scene of nightmarish futility.)
Although this underwrites the contrast between having more and having
less reason to do something, Katsafanas does not regard it as inducing
commensurability of reasons across the board. He does take it to have
consequences for substantive moral theory; for instance, because the
struggle to overcome resistance involves suffering, that sort of
suffering counts as a good thing.</p>

<h2 id="PracViewActi">4. The Practice View of Action</h2>

<p>
In an early, influential, and Wittgenstein-influenced paper, John
Rawls introduced the notion of a <em>practice</em> as a generalization
or extension of the notion of a game (Rawls 1955). The important
feature of a practice for our purposes is that it introduces statuses
which are internal to it; a practice introduces standards. It also
thereby introduces reasons which are internal to it. Baseball involves
statuses such as being a &rsquo;foul&rsquo; or a &rsquo;strike&rsquo;;
whatever you&rsquo;re doing, it can&rsquo;t be a (baseball) foul if
you&rsquo;re not playing baseball. Similarly, something counts as a
&rsquo;home run&rsquo; only by virtue of the standards, given by the
rules of baseball, to which running the bases has to live up. The
reasons within a practice may be means-end or calculative, or they may
be reasons of other kinds. (In squash, that the other player&rsquo;s
head is between your racquet and the ball is a reason to call a
&lsquo;let&rsquo;, not because it is the best way to win; if you were
to hit your opponent in the head, you would win the point. In squash,
calculative reasons are modulated by gentlemanly reasons.)</p>

<p>
Tamar Schapiro has extended Rawls&rsquo;s treatment, developing it
into a theory of action (Schapiro 2001; she attributes the view to
Kant, but again we will not take up the historical question). On her
view, &lsquo;actions&rsquo; are just moves in a completely generic
practice; that is, &lsquo;action&rsquo; is a status within the generic
practice in something like the way that &lsquo;move&rsquo; is a status
within chess. Schapiro does not name the generic practice, but because
it will be convenient to have a way of referring to it, let&rsquo;s
call it &lsquo;Intendo&rsquo;. Intendo is the game you are playing
whenever you do anything at all; &lsquo;agent&rsquo; is thus the
generic role in the generic game (the analog of &lsquo;player,&rsquo;
in chess). Practices specify standards and reasons, and so
&lsquo;practical reasoning&rsquo; turns out to be a practice status as
well. Intendo consequently determines what forms practical reasons can
take, and so patterns of practical inference are read off of what
turns out to be the theory of action.</p>

<p>
Being an action is a status (the generic move) within Intendo; so
there could be no practical reasons coming from outside the practice
of Intendo. (Other, more local practices have to accommodate reasons
that come from outside the practice; for instance, in chess, the
object of the game is to win, but I may have personal reasons for not
playing to win.) Therefore, if you can show that Intendo imposes some
standard on its reasons (and to anticipate, that they have to be
universalizable), then you will have shown that all reasons have to
meet it. An important metaethical question about practical reasoning
has to do with the modality (roughly, the force) of the family of
operators that includes &lsquo;may&rsquo;, &lsquo;must&rsquo;,
&lsquo;should&rsquo;, and so on, when the issue is what you have
reason to do. (Call this the &lsquo;modality of freedom&rsquo;.)
Schapiro&rsquo;s approach provides a surprising answer to this
question: freedom of the will ranges over the allowable moves in the
game of Intendo.</p>

<p>
In extending Rawls&rsquo;s view, Schapiro has departed from it in some
ways. Rawls thought that &lsquo;relatively few actions of the moral
life are defined by practices&rsquo; (op. cit., 32 n.), and worried
about the conservatism implicit in taking &lsquo;the social practices
of [each person&rsquo;s] society to provide the standard of
justification for his actions&rsquo; (32). Rawls took it to be
&lsquo;essential to the notion of a practice that the rules are
publicly known and understood as definitive&rsquo; (24). This cannot
be true of Intendo; if reasons for action were entirely public and
understood as definitive, there would not be a cottage industry of
philosophers arguing about the forms of practical reasoning. And
finally, the Wittgensteinian roots of Rawls&rsquo;s treatment suggest
that he would have been skeptical of a strategy that turned on finding
the deepest common features of all practices. Given that a practice is
an extension of the idea of a game, Wittgenstein famously pointed out
that there is no nontrivial feature common to all games (see Section
3.4, on language games, in the entry on
 <a href="../wittgenstein/">Ludwig Wittgenstein</a>).
 However, to point out that Schapiro&rsquo;s position differs from
Rawls&rsquo;s is of course not thereby to criticize it; rather, it is
to warn against assuming too quickly that her position inherits all of
its structural features.</p>

<p>
Schapiro&rsquo;s article eyes a finish line that is some version of
Kantian morality, one which it is natural to see as a reformulation
and smoothing out of the analogous stretch of Korsgaard&rsquo;s view.
(So this perhaps makes it an additional exception to the earlier
observation that theorists in this subfield don&rsquo;t yet engage one
another.) Schapiro writes that &lsquo;if it is right to think of
universal laws on the model of practice rules, then the law of freedom
can be thought of as an indeterminate practice rule, one which simply
requires us to make every movement as if it were to count as a move in
some possible global practice&rsquo; (108); this is a paraphrase of
the Kantian demand that one act only on maxims of which one could will
that they be universal laws. So, the patterns of practical reasoning
are to be those acknowledged by a Kantian theory of practical
rationality and its substantive moral consequences.</p>

<p>
Schapiro&rsquo;s position is motivated in the first place by the
history of action theory. She identifies two older conceptions of
action, a consequence-oriented view, on which actions are simply ways
of producing effects in a given, natural world, and an expressivist
view, on which actions function more or less as evaluative
pronouncements. The practice view of action is meant to capture the
truth in each of these, while avoiding their defects; it is, as it
were, their Hegelian synthesis. But Schapiro is also motivated by an
appreciation of the importance and value to us of a world enriched by
practice statuses. It is not just that the predecessor theories are
wrong about what an action is; it is that forgoing the textured world
created by our practices would be a terrible mistake. Schapiro&rsquo;s
position is not <em>motivated</em> by anti-psychologism, yet it is
nonetheless non-psychologistic. For instance, when the king is in
check, then the chess player has a reason to move it out of check; you
don&rsquo;t look inside anyone&rsquo;s head, as it were, to determine
that, but rather, at the constitutive rules of chess.</p>

<p>
As before, if the Kantian moral conclusions are to be binding, then
not only must the practice conception entail the Kantian conclusions,
but the practice conception of action must be nonoptional. With
baseball, you can choose not to play, and you can choose to stop
playing; what&rsquo;s more, the rules themselves bring games to a
close. But Intendo must be a game you cannot walk away from. Why
can&rsquo;t you simply start producing activities that are not
practice-governed? We have already gestured at one answer: the
importance of living in a practice-informed world. One further answer
Schapiro might give is that you <em>can&rsquo;t</em> do that &ndash;
where the modality of the &lsquo;can&rsquo;t&rsquo; is the modality of
freedom. (Since reasons are a practice status, questions having to do
with practical reason do not arise for the alternative forms of
activity.)</p>

<p>
The question is especially pressing for Schapiro&rsquo;s. Non-ideal
theory is concerned with guidelines for action and moral thinking in a
world that is not very moral at all. Schapiro 2006 takes up a
traditional Kantian test case, that of the murderer at the door asking
if his intended victim, to whom you have just served a cup of tea, is
at home. Kantian moral theory prohibits lying, and the casuistical
exercise is to provide an explanation, consistent with the moral
theory, of the legitimacy of lying to him. Schapiro&rsquo;s solution
draws on the idea that moral reasons are statuses in the game of
Intendo. If the murderer at the door is refusing to play the game,
then your own moves cannot <em>be</em> responses to his moves &ndash;
in this case, honesty meant as a contribution to the
&lsquo;co-legislation game&rsquo; (the game that properly played
Intendo turns out to be) is simply not an option. And if proper
honesty is not an available move, perhaps other moves are available to
you.</p>

<p>
The tension is this: on the one hand, you must act from the moral law
because you cannot opt out of Intendo; that is why morality is
binding. On the other hand, you may lie to the murderer at the door,
because he <em>has</em> opted out of the game. Schapiro provides a
label for what she intends as a way of splitting the difference: the
murderer is <em>betraying</em> the generic practice without <em>opting
out</em> of it. But the distinction marked by the label is as yet
unexplained. The further development of the practice view will be
shaped by the need to accommodate these apparently conflicting
theoretical constraints.</p>

<h2 id="EvalEsseActi">5. Evaluation as Essential to Action</h2>

<p>
We will review two variants of the thesis that evaluation is an
essential feature of action, or of a privileged kind of action, due
respectively to Sarah Buss and Talbot Brewer.</p>

<p>
Buss distinguishes between mere &ldquo;movements of the human
body&rdquo; and full fledged intentional action by requiring, for the
latter, that agents endorse their actions at the time they are
initiated; the content of the endorsement must in one way or another
come to allowing the agent&rsquo;s reasons to be sufficient for
performing the action (Buss 1999). Anything short of that, she argues,
amounts to adopting a spectatorial stance towards your own actions: if
you identify a number of desires, notice that you could satisfy them
by performing an action, but then don&rsquo;t arrive at an evaluative
belief with roughly the content that that&rsquo;s good enough to go
ahead, you will be doing no more than sitting back to see what happens
&ndash; to see whether the desires actuate your body.</p>

<p>
Buss then considers a Humean moral psychology on which reasons for
action are drawn from two mutually exclusive classes of psychological
states, desires and beliefs, where beliefs are understood to have no
properly evaluative content (e.g., Smith, 1987). Since such a moral
psychology has no room for evaluative beliefs, and since intentional
action requires one particular sort of evaluative belief, Humean moral
psychology is incompatible with there being intentional actions. It
follows that a theory of practical reasoning presupposing Humean moral
psychology cannot allow for intentional action. Theories of practical
reasoning that identify reasons for action with desires and beliefs so
characterized are directed towards choosing actions, yet incompatible
with actions being chosen. The conclusion we are invited to draw is
that Humean theories of practical reasoning are incoherent. A dramatic
way of putting it might be: if your will is to be free,
instrumentalism must be false.</p>

<p>
There is evident overlap between Buss&rsquo;s view and
Velleman&rsquo;s: both pivot on the concern that one act for
one&rsquo;s (sufficient or good enough or best) reasons. (In Velleman,
that concern appears as a desire, where in Buss, it appears as an
evaluation.) But the concern is differently motivated: where Velleman
is trying to halt a regress in the structural analysis of agency, Buss
is trying to express the philosophical thought that action is active
rather than passive. Once past the conclusion that a theory of
practical rationality had better not presuppose a Humean theory of
motivation, Buss is open-minded both about what one&rsquo;s practical
reasons might turn out to be like and about the consequences for moral
theory. Worries about psychologism do not seem to figure into her
view.</p>

<p>
Turning now to Brewer, we encounter a shift of key. In the contrasts
between full-fledged and lower-grade doings that we have reviewed so
far, &ldquo;action&rdquo; was used to designate the first-class
version, and often &ldquo;activity&rdquo; labeled its lesser relative.
Now in Brewer&rsquo;s terminology, <em>dialectical activity</em> is
the privileged category, and actions make up the inferior contrasting
class. Actions are merely structured to produce a
&ldquo;pre-envisioned state of affairs.&rdquo; But dialectical
activity is marked out by two features. First, coming to a better
understanding of what the activity is counts as an essential aspect of
the activity. And second, continually arriving at a deeper
understanding of the good of the activity is an essential aspect of
the activity (Brewer 2009, 55 and <em>passim</em>). For instance, one
might well think that part of what it is to be in a healthy and
satisfactory friendship is to be developing a progressively deeper
sense of what this particular friendship is about, why and how it is
rewarding, what challenges it poses, and how to navigate them.
Moreover, friendship also involves developing an improving
understanding of the demands, rewards, value, and significance of
friendship generally. (The view is positioned as recovering insights
from older ethics, with pride of place to Aristotle, but as before, we
will not take up the historical question.)</p>

<p>
The anchor for the view is not that of our previously surveyed
positions, that to do is thereby to act. (And so Brewer&rsquo;s view
is perhaps a penumbral member of this family of positions.) Rather,
firstly, mere actions typically will not make sense outside the
context of a dialectical activity, and secondly, he advances but does
not quite directly argue for the suggestion that dialectical
activities make up everything that could count as intrinsically
valuable for human beings. Anything that is worthwhile on its own
&ndash; worthwhile enough to be taken seriously from conversation to
philosophy &ndash; belongs in this category.</p>

<p>
Because the proposal is likely to bring to mind specificationist
claims about practical reasoning, some compare and contrast is in
order. Specificationism is built around the observation that,
frequently enough, one&rsquo;s ends are not concrete or definite
enough to launch questions about how to attain them; the content of
one&rsquo;s goals must be filled in and firmed up enough for that to
be possible. Borrowing a low-key example from Bernard Williams (1981a,
104), if our objective is to be entertained this evening, we have to
decide what it will be before we consider the steps to take. So, there
must be a mode of practical thinking that does this job. (For an
overview of the specificationist back and forth, see Millgram, 2008.)
But where the aim of specificationist deliberation is to arrive at a
sufficiently concrete rendering of an objective, in dialectical
activity, the clarification of the activity and its desirability is
ongoing, not just a preliminary. You find out what the rewards of this
friendship are by participating in it, and the longer you are
someone&rsquo;s friend, the more nuanced and deeper your appreciation
of what it brings to your life becomes. Deciding on an evening&rsquo;s
entertainment doesn&rsquo;t usually turn up as part of the fun; with
friendship, however, it is grounds for complaint when one of the
participants ceases paying attention to the emerging shape of the
friendship. Here, deliberation is not simply means-end reasoning;
although one is moved to one after another after another goal-directed
action, those actions are themselves part and parcel of further
comprehending just what the dialectical activity in which they arise
<em>is</em>.</p>

<p>
Adapting one of Brewer&rsquo;s illustrations, two friends might take a
motorcycle trip to Vegas; a few years later, we find them in the
gardening aisle at Home Depot; a few years after that, doing something
very different from either of those things. The relation between
activities and actions as <em>other</em> views conceive them is that
being friends produces an endless stream of subsidiary goals and
actions. But because the participants&rsquo; conception of it
continues to deepen and shift, the actions in that stream cannot be
concretely characterized up front. Brewer&rsquo;s distinction between
high-grade and low-grade are interdependent. Dialectical activity
normally produces merely end-directed action in an ongoing basis. The
intelligibility normally depends on being embedded within a
dialectical activity. (It makes sense that they&rsquo;d be biking to
Vegas, given how, at that stage of the friendship, they understand
what their friendship is about.) The improving grasp of what one is
doing that is central to the activity depends on feedback from the
circumstances produced by the low-grade, end-directed actions; it was,
perhaps, the way the Vegas trip didn&rsquo;t work out that made them
rethink what they were doing with each other, and start in on
gardening.</p>

<p>
On the views Brewer is positioning his own against, actions are
motivated by desires, which are propositional attitudes: descriptions
of states of affairs that might be realized in the future in light of
which you adjust what you can and will so to make them true. (Brewer
attempts to reappropriate the concept of desire for his own purposes,
but I won&rsquo;t spell that move out here.) However, what you are
<em>moved</em> by in the course of a dialectical activity, (as opposed
to &rsquo;motivated&rsquo; by) cannot be captured by a proposition.
For a proposition has a definite, stable content. But what moves you
in the course of dialectical activity is deepening and evolving; there
is no point at which apprehending it is properly over. So no
proposition could successfully demarcate what the activity is after
and about.</p>

<p>
Moreover, desires as standardly conceived treat the proposition as
what is to be made true in the future. But the object of dialectical
activity does not lie in the future: living your life is a dialectical
activity, and you are <em>already</em> living; your life does not wait
to be lived until it is over. If you are somebody&rsquo;s friend, you
are <em>already</em> participating in the friendship. If you are
philosophizing in an appropriately frame of mind (and so, always
striving better to understand what philosophy <em>is</em>), you are
<em>already</em> philosophizing. So, although the many simpler
subsidiary actions that are constantly being spun off by dialectical
activities can often be thought of as controlled by this sort of
propositional attitude, dialectical activity cannot itself be
construed as desire-driven, in this standard sense of
&lsquo;desire&rsquo;.</p>

<p>
What is at stake in the disagreement over how to conceptualize these
ongoing courses of action? In the example we&rsquo;re using, the
friends&rsquo; goals change over time; seen through the lens of
rationalization-by-desires as standardly conceived, the segments of
the friendship are collected into a developing trajectory
retrospectively. The cost is not just that one misses seeing what
unifies the activity while it is in progress; the standard
view&rsquo;s inability to see the activity as unified, despite the
very different character of its segments, undercuts its
<em>actual</em> unity. But then, one does not have <em>that</em>
dialectical activity: a friendship, whose parties are jointly pressing
towards a more truthful, workable, or otherwise better understanding
of that friendship. Operating only on the basis of
rationalization-by-desires condemns one to a life largely empty of the
goods that really matter, such as friendships. Whether this is the
cost of surrendering dialectical activities as Brewer describes them
will depend on whether he is substantively characterizing those
central human goods correctly; an opponent will presumably contest the
view on those grounds.</p>

<p>
Returning to the point of convergence with older specificationism, if
the evolving conception of a dialectical activity and what makes it
desirable is deliberative rather than arational, there must be
reasons, and reasoning, that can modify not only one&rsquo;s decisions
about how to attain what one already straightforwardly wants but also
one&rsquo;s view of what one is after. In the jargon: over and above
instrumental rationality, deliberation of ends must be possible. And
that returns us to the question of the conception of reasons tied to
this contrast between dialectical activity and mere actions. It
shouldn&rsquo;t be possible to simply spell out what practical
reasoning correctly performed must amount to. Practical reasoning is
itself a dialectical activity, so our grasp of what it is will develop
alongside our grasp of the activity. Nonetheless, a number of upshots
for practical rationality stand out in Brewer&rsquo;s discussion.</p>

<p>
First, against the often implicitly accepted model of practical
reasoning as a matter of first surveying surrounding circumstances,
assessing them, and then deciding what action to initiate, one largely
attends to what one is already in the middle of doing, and clarifying
how it has gone hitherto with an eye to a continuation. The model here
is that of an author considering his half-written book, wondering how
to complete his not-fully-formed train of thought &ndash; the one he
is in the middle of expressing. Because understanding what one is
doing does not come all at once but reveals itself as one carries out
the action, there is typically no ability to survey and assess all the
considerations relevant to a decision up front when anything
significant is at stake, as presupposed by the competing model.</p>

<p>
Second, deliberation amounts to asking, &lsquo;<em>What</em> have I
been doing?,&rsquo; and the characterizations driving ongoing
decisions will be largely framed using thick ethical concepts. Rather
than applying concepts like &lsquo;good&rsquo; or &lsquo;right&rsquo;
to evaluatively neutral descriptions of one&rsquo;s activity, they
will deploy descriptions whose application depends on mobilizing
one&rsquo;s evaluative capacities. (Williams 1981b, and for
background, see the entry on
 <a href="../thick-ethical-concepts/">thick ethical concepts</a>.)
 Williams controversially claimed that thick ethical concepts could
not be factored into strictly factual and strictly evaluative
components (for an overview, see Millgram 1995). Brewer argues that
the unity of dialectical activities over time supports
Williams&rsquo;s view on this point, and in addition, that our need to
rely on thick ethical concepts undercuts the distinction we have used
in framing this very survey, between theoretical and practical reasons
&ndash; that is, respectively, reasons that figure into argument about
how the facts stand, and those that figure into arguments for doing
one thing or another.</p>

<p>
Third, and finally for now, Brewer accounts for our qualms about
delegating practical reasoning to others. If practical thought is, as
Brewer puts it, &lsquo;a seamless part of the activity&rsquo; of
friendship, a conversation, philosophy, or just living one&rsquo;s
life, then handing over one&rsquo;s deliberation and decisions to
third parties is to forego the valuable activity itself.</p>

<p>
Although both Buss and Brewer highlight the role of evaluation in
action, for Buss the evaluation that matters is the settled output of
one&rsquo;s evaluating; for Brewer the evaluation that matters is the
evaluat<em>ing</em>.</p>

<h2 id="ProsOutsIssu">6. Prospects and Outstanding Issues</h2>

<p>
The turn to action theory is producing some of the most interesting
recent work on practical reasoning. As we have seen, their shared
methodology notwithstanding, these theorists disagree on just about
everything else: their philosophical reasons for adopting the
approach, the correct theory of practical reasoning, the form or forms
of nonoptional practical inference, and the upshots for morality or
ethics. However, as awareness of the shared agenda grows, we are
starting to see positions that attempt to take on board elements from
more than one of the theories currently in play and, in addition, take
up the task of explaining why competitors are misguided.</p>

<p>
We are also beginning to see pushback against the program as a whole.
Bagnoli 2021 identifies assumptions &ndash; e.g., that actions are
deliberate, purposive, and guided &ndash; that are a bad fit for
improvisation, but which are taken for granted by most theorists
(although some of the theorists we have canvassed gesture in this
direction, for instance, Velleman and perhaps Katsafanas). Arpaly 2020
evinces disbelief that the supposed distinction between action and
mere activity effects a division. The supposed markers of full-fledged
action are matters of degree.</p>

<p>
The primary source of internal disagreements in the subfield is a
disagreement as to what counts as an <em>action</em>. On one view,
intentional actions are characterized by their stepwise or nested
internal structure; on another, by being authored or owned; on a
third, by their place in a practice; on a fourth, by entailing an
evaluation of one&rsquo;s reasons. The norm still is to omit
explanations of why competing conceptions of action are incorrect. In
a famous essay that kicked off discussion of a different topic in
practical reasoning, Robert Nozick observed that advocates of the
alternative responses to Newcomb&rsquo;s Problem were prepared to
explain why they thought their own position correct, but not what was
wrong with arguments for the other alternative; such a posture is
unsatisfactory, and Nozick emphasized that in such debates &lsquo;it
will not do to rest content with one&rsquo;s belief ... nor will it do
to just repeat one of the arguments, loudly and slowly&rsquo; (Nozick
1997, 48).</p>

<p>
It follows that the most important item on the agenda of this research
program is to produce arguments that will decide between the competing
conceptions of action. One can&rsquo;t hang one&rsquo;s theory of
practical reasoning, and one&rsquo;s moral theory to boot, off an
account of action that is treated as obviously false by the others in
one&rsquo;s discipline. We may conclude by observing that there are
two modes of argument one must choose between. One might try to
establish that, as a matter of metaphysical fact, actions <em>are</em>
as this or that theory says; alternatively, one might argue that one
<em>ought</em> to produce actions which are as the theory says; that
is, the top-level argumentation might be either theoretical or
practical.</p>

<p>
The choice between the two modes of argument is tied to a further
strategic choice. On the approach we are examining, theories of
practical inference inherit their bindingness from the non-optionality
of the associated conception of action. That entails that any such
theory needs an answer to the question, &lsquo;Given what is meant by
&ldquo;action&rdquo;, why not produce activity of some <em>other</em>
kind?&rsquo; To canvass the forms this question takes for the theories
we have on the table: Why shouldn&rsquo;t I look for noncalculative
control structures, and manage my activity by using <em>them</em>?
What&rsquo;s wrong with answering the question, &lsquo;Did you really
<em>do</em> (i.e., author) that?&rsquo; with, &lsquo;Well, no, it just
kind of happened?&rsquo; What&rsquo;s wrong with engaging in
activities that compete with each other or frustrate themselves
&ndash; behaving as though you were a market on the inside, rather
than a totalitarian state? Why shouldn&rsquo;t I opt out of the game
of Intendo? Why bother with evaluating the reasons for my action? Why
<em>not</em> detour around activities with the structure of
friendship, philosophizing, and conversation? Notice that we should
not assume without argument that one or another mode of action must be
nonoptional; if the pressures toward one or another form of action
amount to less than practical necessity, pluralism about action might
be the appropriate conclusion (Millgram 2010).</p>

<p>
A theoretical answer would involve showing that there is nothing else
that you <em>can</em> &ndash; metaphysically &ndash; do: that whatever
you do (in the thinnest possible sense) is action (in the
theory&rsquo;s thicker and more substantive sense). A practical answer
would involve showing that, given the alternatives, the suggestion
that you produce actions (in the substantive sense of one&rsquo;s
favored theory) is, as they used to say, an offer you can&rsquo;t
refuse. The type of force or bindingness that one&rsquo;s theory of
practical reason will inherit from one&rsquo;s theory of action will
be determined by the choice between these two modes of argument.</p>
